---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const comparisons = [
    {
        title: 'BEM vs LSCSS',
        href: '/comparisons/bem-vs-lscss/',
        description: 'Naming conventions, modifiers, state classes, and modern CSS architecture.'
    },
    {
        title: 'Tailwind vs LSCSS',
        href: '/comparisons/tailwind-vs-lscss/',
        description: 'Utility-first speed versus semantic structure and long-term maintainability.'
    },
    {
        title: 'CSS Modules vs LSCSS',
        href: '/comparisons/css-modules-vs-lscss/',
        description: 'Component scoping, framework workflows, and system-wide architecture.'
    },
    {
        title: 'Utility-first vs LSCSS',
        href: '/comparisons/utility-first-vs-lscss/',
        description: 'Markup-led styling versus layered semantic CSS systems.'
    },
    {
        title: '@scope and LSCSS',
        href: '/comparisons/scope-vs-lscss/',
        description: 'Native browser scoping and what modern CSS changes for architecture.'
    }
];
---

<DocsLayout
    title="CSS Architecture Comparisons"
    description="Compare BEM, Tailwind, CSS Modules, utility-first CSS, and modern CSS approaches against Layered Semantic CSS."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Comparisons</p>

        <h1>
            CSS architecture comparisons
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Most teams are not choosing CSS from a blank sheet. They are choosing
            between existing habits, inherited pain, and opinions defended like
            family heirlooms. These comparisons focus on trade-offs, not ideology.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Comparison sections">
        <a href="#first">Start first</a>
        <a href="#comparison-guides">Guides</a>
        <a href="#quick-reference">Quick reference</a>
        <a href="#how-to-use">How to use this</a>
        <a href="#starting-point">Where to start</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="first" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Ask this first
        </h2>

        <p>
            Before comparing methodologies, decide what problem you are solving.
            Faster delivery, cleaner ownership, safer scaling, easier onboarding,
            better accessibility, or fewer debugging séances are different goals.
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>If speed today matters most, utility-heavy systems often win early.</li>
            <li>If maintainability matters most, architecture matters more than shortcuts.</li>
            <li>If multiple teams touch the same frontend, predictability becomes expensive to ignore.</li>
            <li>If accessibility and performance matter, discipline beats convenience fast.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="comparison-guides" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Comparison guides
        </h2>

        <p>
            These are not framework popularity contests. They explain where each
            approach helps, where it creates debt, and what happens six months
            after the launch celebration ends.
        </p>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            {
                comparisons.map((item) => (
                    <article class="hub-card">
                        <h3>
                            <a href={item.href}>{item.title}</a>
                        </h3>

                        <p>
                            {item.description}
                        </p>
                    </article>
                ))
            }
        </div>
    </section>

    <section id="quick-reference" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Quick reference
        </h2>

        <table class="comparison-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Approach</th>
                    <th>Main focus</th>
                    <th>Main trade-off</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>

            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>BEM</td>
                    <td>explicit naming and ownership</td>
                    <td>verbosity and naming overhead</td>
                </tr>

                <tr>
                    <td>Tailwind</td>
                    <td>speed and utility-first delivery</td>
                    <td>HTML noise and architectural drift</td>
                </tr>

                <tr>
                    <td>CSS Modules</td>
                    <td>local component scoping</td>
                    <td>scoping without wider system rules</td>
                </tr>

                <tr>
                    <td>@scope</td>
                    <td>native selector boundaries</td>
                    <td>scope without full architecture</td>
                </tr>

                <tr>
                    <td>LSCSS</td>
                    <td>layers, semantics, maintainability</td>
                    <td>requires discipline, not shortcuts</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <p>
            No system removes trade-offs. Good architecture means choosing them
            deliberately instead of inheriting them by accident.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="how-to-use" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            How to use these comparisons
        </h2>

        <p>
            Use these pages when reviewing an inherited codebase, choosing a
            methodology for a new project, or explaining why the current CSS
            setup feels like it was designed during an office fire drill.
        </p>

        <p>
            The goal is not to prove one approach is universally correct. The
            goal is to understand which pain you are choosing to live with.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="starting-point" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Where to start
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/methodology/">Core methodology</a></h3>
                <p>Learn the full system before comparing naming styles and tooling choices.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/decision-trees/">Decision trees</a></h3>
                <p>Use practical rules when a CSS choice stops being obvious.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/playground/">Playground</a></h3>
                <p>Test architecture decisions before they become production folklore.</p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
